%[text] # LLC Resonant Converter Controller Design
%[text] This script enables you to plot the frequency response of the LLC converter and derive the corresponding transfer function. The linearization workflow utilizes time-domain simulation-based frequency response analysis to estimate the transfer function of the LLC converter. You can use the resulting transfer function to design a compensator for the LLC converter.
%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"Table of Contents"}
%[text] ## Load LLC Converter Parameters
% Run this section to set the LLC converter plant parameters
  %[control:button:30c3]{"position":[1,2]}
if ~exist('LLCDesign', 'var')
   LLCConverterDefaultInputParameters;
end
%[text] ## Frequency Response of the LLC Converter
%[text] To estimate the frequency response of the LLC converter, use the Simulink® Control System Toolbox™ to inject a sinestream disturbance into the switching frequency of the Simscape™ model `EstimateFrequencyResponse`.
%[text] To open the model for estimating the frequency response of the LLC converter, enter the following command at the MATLAB® Command Window:
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] open_system("EstimateFrequencyResponse");
%[text] ```
%[text] To estimate the transfer function of the LLC converter, follow these steps:
%[text] 1. **Verify Model Parameters:** Ensure that the `EstimateFrequencyResponse` model is configured with the required parameters.
%[text] 2. **Set Linearization Parameters:** Specify the linearization parameters, including `switchingFrequency` and the sine disturbance `frequencyVector` for which the response is to be estimated.
%[text] 3. **Configure Simulation Periods:** For each frequency in the `frequencyVector`, provide a sufficient number of periods to allow the circuit to reach steady state.
%[text] 4. **Select Disturbance Amplitude:** Choose the sine disturbance per-unit amplitude so that the LLC converter responds appropriately without affecting its natural characteristics.
%[text] 5. **Verify Steady-State Operation:** For each frequency, manually verify that the LLC converter has reached steady state by referring to the provided plot. If steady state is not achieved, increase the settling period.
%[text] 6. **Plot Frequency Response:** To plot the frequency response (Bode plot), run the `plotLLCFrequencyResponse` MATLAB® script.
%[text] 7. **Estimate Transfer Function, Poles, and Zeros:** To estimate the transfer function, poles, and zeros from the LLC frequency response, run the `getLLCPlantPolesAndZero` MATLAB function. \
%%
  %[control:button:9d74]{"position":[1,2]}
% Frequency response model name
freqRespModelName = "EstimateFrequencyResponse";

% Specify the operating conditions at which the LLC converter to be linearized
switchingFrequency = simscape.Value(100e3, "Hz");      % Linearization switching frequency
inputVoltage      = simscape.Value(380, "V");          % Input DC voltage
Rload             = simscape.Value(20.6, "Ohm");       % Output load resistance
steadyStateTime   = simscape.Value(0.03, "s");         % Time to reach steady state at switching frequency

% Sinestream disturbance input parameters
sinestreamStartFreq = simscape.Value(100, "Hz");       % Start frequency of the sinestream disturbance
sinestreamEndFreq   = simscape.Value(71e3, "Hz");      % End frequency of the sinestream disturbance
numFreqPoints       = 30;                              % Number of frequency points in logspace

% Generate frequency vector
frequencyVector = simscape.Value( ...
    linspace(sinestreamStartFreq.value, sinestreamEndFreq.value, numFreqPoints), ...
    "Hz");

% Calculate number of periods for each frequency
numberPeriod = ceil(frequencyVector.value * steadyStateTime.value);

% Sinestream disturbance magnitude (per-unit of resonant frequency)
sinestreamMagnitude = 0.07; % pu

% Estimate frequency response of the plant at the switching frequency
PlotLLCFrequencyResponse; %[output:0220bb1f] %[output:94447f8d]
%%
%[text] ## LLC Converter Transfer Function
%[text] This function generates the transfer function mapping demanded input frequency to output voltage plus its associated poles and zeros.
  %[control:button:4e69]{"position":[1,2]}
systemModel = getLLCPlantPolesAndZero(systemFreqRes,numPole=2,numZero=1); %[output:15a078dd]
%[text] ## LLC Compensator Design
%[text] This design solution implements a compensator with two zeros and two poles (2P2Z). One pole functions as an integrator to improve steady-state performance, while the other pole is positioned to cancel the system zero. The two zeros are placed to cancel the complex conjugate poles of the system, thereby enhancing system stability and transient response.
llcCompensator = getCompensatorPolesAndZero(systemModel,Domain="All",SamplingTime=1e-7); %[output:33369c1f]
%[text] ## LLC Compensator Integrator and Voltage Controlled Oscillator Parameters 
%[text] You can tune the integrator gain of the 2P2Z compensator to achieve the desired performance for the LLC converter controller. Additionally, adjusting the voltage-controlled oscillator (VCO) gain can further optimize the controller’s response and overall system performance.
llcCompensator.Ki = 1; % Integrator gain
llcCompensator.constantVCOGain = 1; % Voltage controlled oscillator gain (Volt/perunit frequency)
llcCompensator.resonantFrequency = LLCSpec.resonantFrequency.value; % Resonant frequency (Hz)
llcCompensator.minPUfrequency = frequencyRange.minFreq/LLCSpec.resonantFrequency.value; % Minimum operating frequency (pu)
llcCompensator.maxPUfrequency = frequencyRange.maxFreq/LLCSpec.resonantFrequency.value; % Maximum operating frequency (pu)
llcCompensator.deadTime = LLCDesign.deadTime;
LLCController.vcoGainVec = [1,1.2]; % Voltage controlled oscillator gain vector (Volt/perunit frequency)

%%
%[text] ## PI Based LLC Controller Parameters
%[text] You can use a PI controller with a suitable voltage-controlled oscillator (VCO) gain to regulate an LLC converter operating with narrow input and output voltage variations.
LLCController.Kp = 3.5; % Proportional controller parameter
LLCController.Ki = 5; % Integral controller parameter
LLCController.Kd = 0; % Differential controller parameter
LLCController.Ts = 1e-6; % Sample time (s)
